

- Inner Join
=============


1) Problem Statement - We Have 2 Tables Courses and Student, We know there is a Student Named as "rahul" & We want to know in which course he has enrolled.


SELECT student_fname, selected_course FROM student;

+---------------+-----------------+
| student_fname | selected_course |
+---------------+-----------------+
| rohit         |               2 |
| shikhar       |               1 |
| rahul         |               4 |
| virat         |               3 |
| kapil         |               1 |
| brain         |               2 |
| carl          |               3 |
| saurabh       |               4 |
+---------------+-----------------+


We can Run the Above Mentioned Query but it will give us the "selected_course" in Number like 1,2,3.... But If we want the name of the course In Which Rahul has Enrolled we can Use the Below Query 

SELECT course_name FROM courses WHERE course_id = (SELECT selected_course FROM student WHERE student_fname = 'rahul');

+-------------+
| course_name |
+-------------+
| devops      |
+-------------+




Solution Using Join   [Inner Join]


SELECT student.student_fname, student.student_lname, courses.course_name FROM student JOIN courses ON student.selected_course = courses.course_id;

+---------------+---------------+-----------------+
| student_fname | student_lname | course_name     |
+---------------+---------------+-----------------+
| shikhar       | dhawan        | big data        |
| kapil         | dev           | big data        |
| rohit         | sharma        | web development |
| brain         | lara          | web development |
| virat         | kohli         | data science    |
| carl          | hooper        | data science    |
| rahul         | dravid        | devops          |
| saurabh       | ganguly       | devops          |
+---------------+---------------+-----------------+









